# 'BlinkDigits' by Richard Langner
## Bink out numbers on a single LED.

BlinkDigits can blink an LED to display any number from 0 to 99999.<br>
aEach digit of the number is represented by a number of flashes, 
e.g. 3 is flashed briefly three times, 9 flashes briefly nine times, and a 0 is represented by a long flash.<br><br>
After each digit there is a brief pause before the next digit is flashed.<br>
When all digits in your number have been flashed, there is a longer pause, and then it all repeats.<br>
Each time a number is completed, the function returns true.<br>
## How to use FlashDigits
Include the header file in your program :<br>
`#include "FlashDigits.h"`<br><br>
Create a BlinkDigits object :<br>
`BlinkDigits flasher1;`<br><br>
In your loop() add the code :<br>
`flasher1.blink ( ledPin, LOW, myNumber )`,<br>
where ledPin is the pin number of the LED ( or use LED_BUILTIN ), LOW ( or HIGH ) to define the level required to turn on the LED, and lastly the number you want to blink (0-99999).<br>
BlinkDigits returns 'true' when all the digits have been flashed.<br>
## Example code
Here is an example which blinks out 23.<br>

`#include "BlinkDigits.h"`<br>
`BlinkDigits flasher1;`<br>
`int ledPin = D4;`<br>

`int myNumber=23;`<br>

`void setup() {`<br>
`	pinMode(ledPin, OUTPUT);`<br>
`}`<br>

`void loop() {`<br>
`    flasher1.blink(ledPin, LOW, myNumber);`<br>
`}`<br>

If you want to blink out leading zeros, for example 023, simply state the number of places you want - using the 'width' parameter - in this case 3.

`flasher1.blink(ledPin, LOW, myNumber,3);`<br><br>
There is better example in 'main.cpp' which also write to Serial.
## All timings are adjustable.
 Here we slow things right down.<br>
`flasher1.config(400,1500,800, 5000); // slower timings.`<br>
You specify the four parameters : on/off digit flash time, the zero time, the delay between digits, and the delay before repeating the number.<br>
Defaults are 200,1000,500, 3000.
## How can BlinkDigits improve my project?
- Use as a heartbeat LED which gives the status of the program.<br>
- When connected to wifi, blink out the last 3 digits of the IP address, so you know where to find your device on the network.<br>
- Indicate an analog reading.
